<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ephedra funerea </i>is endemic to the northern and central Mojave Desert and southern Great Basin in western Nevada and adjacent eastern California. It is probably relatively long-lived and can persist through long droughts. It may be able to sprout after disturbance; damage from rock falls and other mechanical disturbances is likely to initiate sprouting. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance occupies rugged slopes and ridges on calcareous substrates. <i>E. funerea </i>is the strong dominant in stands, where it forms short-stature and open stands at no greater than 10% cover. Soil appears too rocky and nutrient deficient for <i>Coleogyne ramosissima </i>or <i>Larrea tridentata </i>to attain high cover, while <i>E. funerea </i>is a regular component of the <i>Coleogyne ramosissima, Larrea tridentata-Ambrosia dumosa, </i>and <i>Larrea tridentata-Encelia farinosa </i>alliances in calcareous mountains that have finer sediments or gentler slopes. However, we need more sampling to clarify its relationships with other alliances that occur on calcareous substrates and to understand its seral trends.<br/>
<br/>
This alliance was cited as <i>Ephedra funerea</i> Provisional Shrubland Alliance in the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
